# yangble5 — nginx server-block snippet for an EXISTING vhost
# =============================================================================
# WHAT THIS IS
#
#   The nginx equivalent of deploy/Caddyfile, for the case where you already
#   run nginx on 80/443 and cannot hand those ports to Caddy. Pair it with
#   deploy/docker-compose.behind-proxy.yml, which publishes the gateway on
#   127.0.0.1 only and starts no Caddy at all.
#
#   internet ──443──▶ THIS nginx ──127.0.0.1:8081──▶ gateway ──▶ engine ──▶ upstream
#
# WHAT THIS IS NOT
#
#   Not a complete nginx config. There is no `listen`, no `ssl_certificate`,
#   no `server_name` here on purpose: you already have those, they already
#   work, and rewriting them is how a working vhost stops working. Copy the
#   marked blocks INTO your existing `server { ... }`.
#
#   For aaPanel / BT panel — where the panel owns the vhost file and will
#   rewrite it — read AAPANEL.md first. It tells you which file to put this
#   in so a panel update does not delete it.
#
# HONEST STATUS
#
#   This file has never been loaded by nginx. It was checked for balanced
#   braces and terminating semicolons by a script, and every directive was
#   chosen against gateway/app.py and deploy/docker-compose.behind-proxy.yml.
#   `nginx -t` is YOUR step and it is not optional — see AAPANEL.md §5.
#
# THE FIVE THINGS THAT SILENTLY BREAK STREAMING
#
#   Naive nginx defaults do not error. They make the agent look frozen for
#   thirty seconds and then dump the whole answer at once, or cut the stream
#   at sixty seconds with a truncated reply. All five are fixed below and each
#   one is commented where it appears:
#
#     1. proxy_buffering on           (default)  — collects the whole SSE
#                                                  stream before sending a byte
#     2. proxy_read_timeout 60s       (default)  — kills any generation that
#                                                  thinks for longer than a minute
#     3. proxy_http_version 1.0       (default)  — no chunked upstream request,
#                                                  and Connection: close per call
#     4. Connection header passed through        — upgrade/close tokens leak to
#                                                  the gateway
#     5. gzip over text/event-stream             — buffers a compression window
#                                                  before flushing anything
# =============================================================================


# =============================================================================
# PART 0 — http { } CONTEXT (OPTIONAL, AND OFTEN NOT AVAILABLE)
# =============================================================================
#
# These two directives are the ONLY ones in this file that cannot live inside
# a server block. On a panel-managed host you usually cannot edit the http
# context safely, so BOTH are optional and everything below works without
# them. Skip this whole part unless you own /www/server/nginx/conf/nginx.conf.
#
# --- 0a. Upstream keepalive (a real, measurable saving) ----------------------
#
# Without an `upstream` block nginx opens a NEW TCP connection to the gateway
# for every single request. On loopback that costs little, but it also means
# `proxy_http_version 1.1` and the cleared Connection header below buy you no
# connection reuse — they are still required (see PART 2) for chunked request
# bodies and for not leaking hop-by-hop tokens, but keepalive itself needs this:
#
#   upstream yangble5_gateway {
#       server 127.0.0.1:8081;      # must equal GATEWAY_PORT in deploy/.env
#       keepalive 32;               # idle connections kept per worker
#       keepalive_timeout 120s;
#       keepalive_requests 1000;
#   }
#
# Then change every `proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081` below to
# `proxy_pass http://yangble5_gateway`.
#
# --- 0b. Rate limiting (limit_req_zone is http-context ONLY) -----------------
#
# There is no server-level equivalent. If you cannot add these, say so out
# loud in your own notes: in reverse-proxy mode the gateway's own limits
# (YANGBLE5_AUTH_RPM_PER_IP, YANGBLE5_RATE_LIMIT_RPM) and Cloudflare are the
# ONLY request-rate defences you have. The Caddyfile's rate_limit zones do not
# exist in this deployment.
#
#   limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=yb5_auth:10m rate=10r/m;
#   limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=yb5_api:10m  rate=120r/m;
#   limit_req_status 429;
#
# $binary_remote_addr is correct ONLY if the real_ip block in PART 1 is in
# place. Without it every request is keyed on the Cloudflare edge that
# forwarded it, so one abusive client throttles thousands of innocent ones.
#
# Where to apply them is marked `# limit_req zone=...` in PART 3.


# =============================================================================
# EVERYTHING BELOW GOES INSIDE YOUR EXISTING  server { ... }  BLOCK
# =============================================================================


    # =========================================================================
    # PART 1 — WHO IS THE CLIENT
    # =========================================================================
    #
    # gateway/app.py::client_ip decides per-IP rate limits, the auth-failure
    # lockout and the "one key seen from N addresses" abuse signal. Get this
    # wrong and all three fire on the wrong address — usually a Cloudflare
    # edge, which means one bad actor gets thousands of strangers locked out.
    #
    # --- 1a. Cloudflare: recover the visitor's address ----------------------
    #
    # With a proxied (orange-cloud) record, $remote_addr is a Cloudflare edge
    # server. ngx_http_realip_module rewrites $remote_addr to the address in
    # CF-Connecting-IP, but ONLY for connections that came from one of the
    # set_real_ip_from ranges. That restriction is the entire security
    # property: without it, anyone who reaches your origin directly can set
    # CF-Connecting-IP to whatever they like and become any IP they want.
    #
    # Confirm the module is compiled in before relying on this:
    #     nginx -V 2>&1 | tr ' ' '\n' | grep -- --with-http_realip_module
    #
    # DELETE THIS ENTIRE SUB-BLOCK IF YOU ARE NOT BEHIND CLOUDFLARE.
    # $remote_addr is then already the real client and nothing else changes.
    #
    # ⚠ THIS LIST GOES STALE. Cloudflare adds ranges. A missing range does not
    # error — it silently leaves $remote_addr as the edge address for the
    # clients arriving through it. Regenerate it yourself, on your own host,
    # and re-check quarterly:
    #
    #     { curl -fsS https://www.cloudflare.com/ips-v4;
    #       curl -fsS https://www.cloudflare.com/ips-v6; } \
    #     | sed 's|^|set_real_ip_from |; s|$|;|' \
    #     > /www/server/panel/vhost/nginx/cloudflare_real_ip.conf
    #
    # ...then replace the literal list below with:
    #     include /www/server/panel/vhost/nginx/cloudflare_real_ip.conf;
    #
    # The literal copy below is a STARTING POINT transcribed from Cloudflare's
    # published list. It was not fetched or verified from this machine. Treat
    # the curl output as authoritative, not this file.

    set_real_ip_from 173.245.48.0/20;
    set_real_ip_from 103.21.244.0/22;
    set_real_ip_from 103.22.200.0/22;
    set_real_ip_from 103.31.4.0/22;
    set_real_ip_from 141.101.64.0/18;
    set_real_ip_from 108.162.192.0/18;
    set_real_ip_from 190.93.240.0/20;
    set_real_ip_from 188.114.96.0/20;
    set_real_ip_from 197.234.240.0/22;
    set_real_ip_from 198.41.128.0/17;
    set_real_ip_from 162.158.0.0/15;
    set_real_ip_from 104.16.0.0/13;
    set_real_ip_from 104.24.0.0/14;
    set_real_ip_from 172.64.0.0/13;
    set_real_ip_from 131.0.72.0/22;
    set_real_ip_from 2400:cb00::/32;
    set_real_ip_from 2606:4700::/32;
    set_real_ip_from 2803:f800::/32;
    set_real_ip_from 2405:b500::/32;
    set_real_ip_from 2405:8100::/32;
    set_real_ip_from 2a06:98c0::/29;
    set_real_ip_from 2c0f:f248::/32;

    # CF-Connecting-IP holds exactly one address and Cloudflare overwrites it
    # on every request, so it cannot be forged through the edge. Prefer it to
    # X-Forwarded-For, which the visitor can prepend entries to.
    real_ip_header CF-Connecting-IP;

    # off = trust the header as a single value from the immediate peer.
    # `on` walks X-Forwarded-For right-to-left and is only correct when
    # real_ip_header is X-Forwarded-For. With CF-Connecting-IP it is wrong.
    real_ip_recursive off;

    # --- 1b. What the gateway is told ---------------------------------------
    # (the proxy_set_header directives themselves live in PART 2)
    #
    # We OVERWRITE X-Forwarded-For with $remote_addr rather than appending
    # with $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for. After PART 1a, $remote_addr is already
    # the true visitor, so the header the gateway receives has exactly ONE
    # entry and nothing a client sent can survive into it.
    #
    # This is what makes YANGBLE5_TRUSTED_PROXY_HOPS=1 correct. client_ip()
    # reads the entry HOPS-from-the-END of the list:
    #
    #   nginx sets X-Forwarded-For to        | header the gateway sees        | HOPS
    #   -------------------------------------+--------------------------------+-----
    #   $remote_addr        (THIS FILE)      | visitor                        | 1
    #   $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for, no CF    | visitor                        | 1
    #   $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for, behind   | visitor, cf-edge               | 2
    #     CF, realip NOT configured          |                                |
    #   $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for, behind   | forged, visitor, cf-edge       | 2
    #     CF, client sent a forged XFF       |   (still resolves to visitor)  |
    #
    # A wrong HOPS value fails silently and in the dangerous direction: the
    # gateway rate-limits a Cloudflare edge address instead of the abuser.
    # Set YANGBLE5_TRUSTED_PROXY_HOPS=1 in deploy/.env to match this file.
    #
    # If ngx_http_realip_module is NOT available, the fallback is
    #     proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $http_cf_connecting_ip;
    # which is spoofable by anyone who can reach the origin directly. Only do
    # that with the origin firewalled to Cloudflare's ranges
    # (`harden.sh --cloudflare-only`), and never on a grey-cloud record.


    # =========================================================================
    # PART 2 — SERVER-LEVEL PROXY BEHAVIOUR  (the streaming-critical part)
    # =========================================================================
    #
    # WHY THESE ARE AT SERVER LEVEL, NOT REPEATED PER LOCATION
    #
    #   Every proxy_* directive here is inherited by each `location` that has
    #   a proxy_pass, and inert everywhere else. One declaration site means
    #   the API paths in PART 3 cannot drift apart — a real failure mode, and
    #   an ugly one, because the surviving symptom is "streaming works on
    #   /v1/messages but not on /api/v1/messages".
    #
    #   ⚠ INHERITANCE IS ALL-OR-NOTHING FOR proxy_set_header. If you ever add
    #   ONE proxy_set_header inside a location, that location loses ALL FOUR
    #   set below, and the gateway starts seeing 127.0.0.1 as every client.
    #   Add headers here, not there.
    #
    #   ⚠ These also apply to any OTHER proxy_pass in this vhost. That is fine
    #   for a vhost dedicated to yangble5 and wrong if you share it. If you
    #   share it, move PART 2 into each yangble5 location instead and accept
    #   the duplication.

    # --- 2a. Identity and scheme --------------------------------------------
    proxy_set_header Host              $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP         $remote_addr;
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For   $remote_addr;   # overwrite, see 1b
    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;

    # --- 2b. HTTP/1.1 to the gateway, and a cleared Connection header -------
    #
    # NOT related to the HTTP/2 or HTTP/3 you serve to browsers. This is the
    # loopback hop only, and nginx's default there is HTTP/1.0.
    #
    # 1.0 has no chunked transfer encoding, so with proxy_request_buffering
    # off (2d) nginx must buffer the whole request body to compute a
    # Content-Length — which is precisely the multi-megabyte prompt upload
    # we are trying not to spool to disk.
    #
    # The empty Connection value is required for two separate reasons:
    #   * it stops the client's Connection header (`close`, `Upgrade`) from
    #     being forwarded as a hop-by-hop directive to the gateway;
    #   * it is the prerequisite for upstream keepalive if you add the
    #     `upstream` block from PART 0a.
    proxy_http_version 1.1;
    proxy_set_header Connection "";

    # --- 2c. THE ONE THAT BREAKS SSE ----------------------------------------
    #
    # Default is `on`: nginx reads the whole upstream response into memory or
    # a temp file before sending anything downstream. For a token stream that
    # converts "words appearing as they are generated" into "nothing for 40
    # seconds, then everything at once". The agent looks hung; users report a
    # crash that never happened.
    #
    # gateway/app.py already sets `X-Accel-Buffering: no` on every
    # text/event-stream response and nginx honours it per-response — but only
    # for responses it recognises as streams. Turning buffering off outright
    # also covers long non-SSE responses and any future content type.
    proxy_buffering off;

    # --- 2d. Request-side buffering -----------------------------------------
    #
    # Default `on` spools the entire request body before contacting the
    # gateway. Our measured prompt is ~749K tokens ≈ several MB of JSON; with
    # buffering on, every one of those requests is written to
    # /var/lib/nginx/body first, adding disk I/O and latency to the largest
    # requests you have. Off streams it straight through.
    #
    # Trade-off, stated plainly: with request buffering off nginx cannot
    # retry the request against another upstream, because the body is already
    # consumed. There is exactly one upstream here, so there is nothing to
    # retry against.
    proxy_request_buffering off;

    # --- 2e. Timeouts -------------------------------------------------------
    #
    # nginx's default proxy_read_timeout is 60s and it is measured BETWEEN
    # successive reads, not over the whole response — so a stream that emits
    # a token every second survives it, and a long "thinking" pause before
    # the first token does not.
    #
    # Measured on this project (docs/BENCHMARK.md, one Windows 11 machine,
    # one run per configuration, ~749K-token prompt), end-to-end round times:
    #   round 1 (cold) 21,410 ms · round 2 10,753 ms · round 3 23,457 ms
    #   · round 4 22,381 ms.
    # Two of the three warm rounds were SLOWER than the cold round; nothing
    # here claims a latency improvement. What it does establish is that a
    # single legitimate request can take ~25 s of wall clock, which is why
    # 60 s is not enough headroom and 600 s is not paranoid.
    proxy_connect_timeout 10s;      # loopback: if this is slow, it is down
    proxy_send_timeout    600s;     # uploading a multi-MB prompt body
    proxy_read_timeout    600s;     # between reads, incl. time to first token

    # Downstream counterpart. Default 60s: nginx would abandon a slow CLIENT
    # mid-stream even though the gateway is still producing tokens happily.
    send_timeout 600s;

    # ⚠ CLOUDFLARE CAPS THIS ABOVE YOU. On Free/Pro/Business plans the edge
    # gives up ~100 s after the request and returns 524, regardless of the
    # 600 s here. It applies to time-to-FIRST-BYTE, so streaming responses
    # are safe once the first SSE event is out. A non-streaming call that
    # thinks for two minutes is NOT — it will 524 no matter what this file
    # says. deploy/cloudflare.md §4 has the options (grey-cloud the API
    # hostname, or require stream=true).

    # --- 2f. Keep the buffers sane if someone re-enables buffering ----------
    # Inert while proxy_buffering is off. Present so that turning buffering
    # back on for debugging does not also introduce a 4K buffer that stalls
    # on large SSE headers.
    proxy_buffer_size       16k;
    proxy_buffers        8  16k;
    proxy_busy_buffers_size 32k;

    # --- 2g. Never cache an inference response ------------------------------
    # Responses contain user data and are not idempotent. If a cache is
    # configured at http level, this opts this vhost out of it.
    proxy_cache off;
    proxy_no_cache 1;
    proxy_cache_bypass 1;

    # --- 2h. Body size ------------------------------------------------------
    # Must be >= YANGBLE5_MAX_REQUEST_BYTES (33554432 = 32m). If nginx's limit
    # is the smaller of the two, the client gets a bare nginx 413 HTML page
    # instead of the gateway's JSON error and no usage is recorded.
    # Cloudflare's own Free-plan upload cap is 100 MB, so this is the binding
    # limit, not CF.
    client_max_body_size 32m;
    client_body_timeout  120s;

    # --- 2i. Do not advertise the stack -------------------------------------
    server_tokens off;
    proxy_hide_header X-Powered-By;

    # --- 2j. Response headers ------------------------------------------------
    #
    # ⚠⚠ THIS IS THE PART THAT DID NOT GET PASTED ON yangble5.com ITSELF. ⚠⚠
    #
    # Observed 2026-07-22 from off-host: the live site served exactly ONE of
    # the headers below — `strict-transport-security: max-age=31536000`,
    # WITHOUT `includeSubDomains`, i.e. not the value written on this page.
    # That one came from Cloudflare's own HSTS toggle. Everything else — CSP,
    # nosniff, X-Frame-Options, Referrer-Policy, both Cross-Origin-* headers,
    # Permissions-Policy — was absent, and /install.sh was served as
    # `application/octet-stream` with nothing telling the browser not to sniff
    # it. Nothing errored. `nginx -t` was fine. The post-deploy smoke test was
    # green, because the only header it looked for was HSTS and Cloudflare had
    # already supplied one.
    #
    # ⚠ CLOUDFLARE ADDS NONE OF THESE. A proxied (orange-cloud) zone passes
    # origin response headers through; it does not invent security headers.
    # Being behind Cloudflare is not a reason to skip this part — it is the
    # reason the gap stays invisible, because CF's own HSTS makes a "is there
    # any security header at all" check pass against an origin that sets none.
    #
    # ── PREFER THE INCLUDE, NOT THE PASTE ────────────────────────────────────
    #
    # The failure mode above is "a block you have to remember to paste".
    # deploy/nginx/security-headers.conf holds exactly the directives below as
    # one self-contained unit. Copy that file to the host and replace this
    # whole sub-part with ONE line, at server level:
    #
    #     include /etc/nginx/yangble5/security-headers.conf;
    #
    # Either the include is there and ALL of it applies, or the path is wrong
    # and `nginx -t` FAILS LOUDLY. There is no half-applied state, and
    # half-applied is the only state that actually hurt here. That file's own
    # header comment carries the install command and the aaPanel-safe path.
    #
    # The directives are kept inline below as well, so that pasting this file
    # verbatim still ends up secure.
    # tests/test_deploy_security_headers.py asserts the two copies are
    # identical, so they cannot drift apart.
    #
    # ── AND THE GOTCHA THAT DELETES ALL OF IT ────────────────────────────────
    #
    # ⚠ NGINX GOTCHA, AND IT IS THE ONE PEOPLE GET WRONG: add_header does NOT
    # merge across levels. A location containing a single add_header of its
    # own silently drops EVERY add_header declared here. That is how sites
    # lose HSTS on exactly the paths that matter.
    #
    # So: all of them are declared once, here, and the API locations in
    # PART 3 declare none. Where a value must differ per location, it is a
    # variable set with `set` (which DOES override cleanly per location). If
    # you genuinely must add one inside a location, re-`include` the headers
    # file inside that location too.
    #
    # `always` makes them apply to error responses too — a 429 or a 502 needs
    # HSTS and nosniff exactly as much as a 200 does.
    #
    # THEN VERIFY FROM OFF-HOST. A check run on the VPS bypasses Cloudflare
    # and tells you nothing about what the internet receives:
    #
    #     bash deploy/smoke_test.sh --base-url https://your.domain --no-spend
    #
    # Check 9 in that script FAILS — not warns — if any header below is
    # missing. A config whose security headers are absent is not deployed.

    # Cache policy. Default is the static-site value; API locations override
    # it to no-store via `set $yb5_cc`.
    set $yb5_cc "public, max-age=300";

    add_header Cache-Control $yb5_cc always;

    # `no-transform` (set on the API paths) is the standards-based way to
    # tell Cloudflare — an intermediary you do not control — not to re-encode
    # or buffer the body. Without it a proxied zone may transform a
    # text/event-stream response and the agent sits there looking frozen.

    # Advisory for any FURTHER proxy in front of this one. Note that nginx
    # hides the gateway's own X-Accel-Buffering header by default (it is in
    # the built-in proxy_hide_header list, because nginx consumes it), so
    # this re-adds the signal for an outer hop. Cloudflare does not act on
    # it; `proxy_buffering off` in 2c is what actually does the work here.
    add_header X-Accel-Buffering "no" always;

    # 1 year. `preload` deliberately NOT set: submitting to the preload list
    # is effectively irreversible for the domain AND every subdomain, and
    # this box serves other sites.
    add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains" always;

    # Not decorative here: PART 3d serves .sh and .ps1 straight out of the
    # webroot with a Content-Type nginx had to guess. Without nosniff a
    # browser is free to sniff a shell script into something else.
    add_header X-Content-Type-Options "nosniff" always;

    add_header Referrer-Policy "no-referrer" always;
    add_header X-Frame-Options "DENY" always;
    add_header Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy "same-origin" always;
    add_header Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy "same-origin" always;
    add_header Permissions-Policy "geolocation=(), microphone=(), camera=(), payment=(), usb=()" always;

    # Scoped to the static pages in site/. They use inline <style> (allowed)
    # and exactly ONE inline <script> each, pinned below by sha256. The two
    # hashes are site/index.html's and site/verify.html's script blocks, in
    # that order; they change whenever either <script> is edited, and
    # site/README.md carries the recompute snippet. If you edit a page and
    # forget this line, the page still renders — copy buttons, OS detection
    # and the live pool status simply stop working, silently.
    # tests/test_deploy_security_headers.py recomputes both hashes from the
    # real pages, so a stale pin is a red test rather than a silent breakage.
    #
    # Do not "fix" a CSP violation by adding 'unsafe-inline' to script-src on
    # a page whose entire job is convincing a visitor it is safe to paste a
    # command into a shell.
    add_header Content-Security-Policy "default-src 'self'; img-src 'self' data:; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; script-src 'self' 'sha256-azlzgFYelw1E8Ku3E8GqYH1fE6nmHMTP3Cy/CCWrGT8=' 'sha256-4FFG4w4T/7cQdRclDwWnwwb3pZxhyUhWrDX0fSl2niI=' ; connect-src 'self'; frame-ancestors 'none'; base-uri 'none'; form-action 'self'" always;


    # =========================================================================
    # PART 3 — ROUTING
    # =========================================================================
    #
    # ⚠ WHY EVERY BLOCK BELOW USES `^~` OR `=` AND NEVER A REGEX
    #
    # Panel-generated vhosts routinely contain a line like
    #
    #     location ~ .*\.(js|css)?$ { expires 12h; }
    #
    # The `?` makes the extension OPTIONAL, so that regex matches EVERY URI,
    # including /v1/messages. Regex locations are tried in file order and beat
    # ordinary prefix locations, so if that block sits above yours, your API
    # is served from the webroot and every client gets 404 — with no error at
    # reload time and nothing in the log to explain it.
    #
    # `^~` and `=` outrank ALL regex locations regardless of order. That
    # immunity is the reason for the notation; do not "tidy" it away.

    # --- 3a. HARD BLOCK: the engine's management surface --------------------
    #
    # CLIProxyAPI's /v0/management/* can list, mint and export upstream
    # credentials, read the usage queue and rewrite config. It must never be
    # reachable from the internet. This is the outermost of three locks; the
    # others are (1) the engine has no published port in
    # docker-compose.behind-proxy.yml and (2) it still demands a management
    # key. deploy/smoke_test.sh asserts this returns 404 from outside.
    #
    # 404, not 403: a 403 confirms to a scanner that the path exists.
    #
    # `^~ /v0` also matches /v0anything. That over-match is deliberate — the
    # gateway has no route starting with /v0, so nothing legitimate is lost.
    location ^~ /v0 {
        return 404;
    }

    # Probes for the engine's debug/admin surfaces, and for the two files
    # that leak everything if they are ever copied into a webroot.
    location ^~ /management {
        return 404;
    }
    location ^~ /debug/ {
        return 404;
    }
    location = /metrics {
        return 404;
    }

    # Dotfiles. The negative lookahead keeps /.well-known/acme-challenge/
    # working, which your existing certificate renewal depends on.
    # This one is a regex because it must not swallow .well-known; it is
    # placed before the static handler and matches nothing the API uses.
    location ~ ^/\.(?!well-known) {
        deny all;
        return 404;
    }

    # --- 3b. The gateway's own admin API ------------------------------------
    #
    # /admin/* mints invite codes, lists keys and flips account status. It is
    # authenticated (YANGBLE5_ADMIN_API_KEY) and it already 404s an
    # unauthenticated caller, but there is no reason for it to be on the
    # public internet at all: you are the only user and you have SSH.
    #
    # From the VPS:  curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $ADMIN_KEY" \
    #                     http://127.0.0.1:8081/admin/keys
    #
    # If you genuinely need it remotely, replace `return 404` with the
    # proxy_pass line and an allow/deny list — and remember `allow` is
    # matched against $remote_addr, which PART 1a has already rewritten to
    # the real visitor, so your office IP works as written:
    #
    #     allow 203.0.113.7;
    #     deny all;
    #     set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
    #     proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081;
    location ^~ /admin {
        return 404;
    }

    # ⚠ AND THE SAME PATH THROUGH THE /api/ ALIAS.
    #
    # This block is not redundant, and leaving it out is a real hole. The
    # `location ^~ /api/` block in 3c strips its own prefix before proxying,
    # so WITHOUT this, `/api/admin/keys` arrives at the gateway as
    # `/admin/keys` — the admin surface, published to the internet, past a
    # `location ^~ /admin { return 404; }` that looks like it covers it.
    #
    # nginx picks the LONGEST matching `^~` prefix, so /api/admin wins over
    # /api/ and the alias stays closed. If you ever add another blocked
    # prefix above, add its /api/ twin here too.
    #
    # This was found by cross-checking every gateway route against the
    # location table, not by reading the file. Do the same after you edit it.
    location ^~ /api/admin {
        return 404;
    }

    # Same reasoning, defence in depth: /api/v0/... would be forwarded to the
    # GATEWAY as /v0/..., which 404s anyway because the gateway uses a route
    # allowlist with no catch-all. Blocked here so the promise "no engine
    # management path is reachable" holds at the edge, where it is auditable,
    # rather than depending on a property of the application behind it.
    location ^~ /api/v0 {
        return 404;
    }

    # --- 3c. THE API ---------------------------------------------------------
    #
    # Each block is deliberately tiny: PART 2 already supplied the streaming
    # settings, the headers and the timeouts. What is left per location is
    # (1) turn gzip off, (2) mark the response uncacheable, (3) proxy_pass.
    #
    # `gzip off` is per-location because the static site in 3d SHOULD be
    # compressed. Compressing a text/event-stream makes nginx hold a
    # compression window's worth of tokens before flushing — the same frozen
    # agent as proxy_buffering, from a different direction. Stock gzip_types
    # does not list text/event-stream, but panel configs get edited, and a
    # `gzip_types text/*` added six months from now would break streaming
    # with no other trace.
    #
    # `proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081` — the LITERAL IP, never `localhost`.
    # docker-compose.behind-proxy.yml binds 127.0.0.1 only, not [::1]; on a
    # dual-stack host the resolver may hand nginx ::1 and every request fails
    # with "Connection refused" while `ss -ltnp` clearly shows the port open.
    #
    # ⚠ THE PORT MUST MATCH GATEWAY_PORT IN deploy/.env — and note that
    # deploy/.env.example ships GATEWAY_PORT=8000 for the standalone stack,
    # while docker-compose.behind-proxy.yml defaults to 8081. Pick one. If
    # you keep 8000, change all four proxy_pass lines below. If you keep
    # 8081, put GATEWAY_PORT=8081 in deploy/.env. A mismatch shows up as 502.

    # SDK base URL. Anthropic/OpenAI-shaped clients are configured with
    # https://yangble5.com/v1 and append /messages, /chat/completions,
    # /responses, /models themselves. This is the streaming path.
    location ^~ /v1/ {
        gzip off;
        set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
        # limit_req zone=yb5_api burst=20 nodelay;   # needs PART 0b
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081;
    }

    # Registration and key management. Small JSON POSTs, but they share the
    # streaming-safe settings because there is no reason for them not to.
    # This is the credential-guessing surface: if you have PART 0b, the
    # STRICT zone belongs here, not the API one.
    location ^~ /auth/ {
        gzip off;
        set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
        # limit_req zone=yb5_auth burst=5 nodelay;   # needs PART 0b
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081;
    }

    # The /api/* alias. site/index.html's status widget fetches /api/health
    # first (then /health, then /healthz — first success wins), and this also
    # gives you one prefix that reaches every gateway route without listing
    # them: /api/usage, /api/byok, /api/pool/status, /api/v1/messages, ...
    #
    # The trailing slash on proxy_pass is what strips the /api/ prefix:
    # /api/v1/messages is passed upstream as /v1/messages. Removing that
    # slash would forward /api/v1/messages verbatim and the gateway, which
    # uses an explicit route allowlist and no catch-all, would 404 it.
    #
    # Side effect of the URI form: nginx passes the NORMALISED, decoded URI.
    # No yangble5 route carries percent-encoded path segments, so this is
    # safe here — but it is why the /v1/ block above has no trailing slash.
    location ^~ /api/ {
        gzip off;
        set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
        # limit_req zone=yb5_api burst=20 nodelay;   # needs PART 0b
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081/;
    }

    # Root-level singles. These exist because deploy/smoke_test.sh and
    # site/install.sh call them at the root, not under /api/. `=` is an exact
    # match, so /healthy or /health/x are NOT matched and fall through to the
    # static site as a 404 — which is what you want.
    #
    # /health is canonical. gateway/app.py stacks @app.get("/healthz") on the
    # same handler, so the alias below is belt-and-braces rather than a
    # rewrite the app depends on — it keeps working if that decorator is ever
    # removed. site/index.html probes /api/health, then /health, then
    # /healthz, first success wins; all three answer with this file in place.
    location = /health {
        gzip off;
        set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081;
    }
    location = /healthz {
        gzip off;
        set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081/health;
    }
    location = /pool/status {
        gzip off;
        set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081;
    }
    location = /usage {
        gzip off;
        set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081;
    }
    location = /byok {
        gzip off;
        set $yb5_cc "no-store, no-transform";
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8081;
    }

    # --- 3d. THE STATIC SITE -------------------------------------------------
    #
    # Everything not matched above is served from the webroot. Copy the
    # contents of site/ there — index.html, verify.html, install.sh,
    # install.ps1, uninstall.sh, uninstall.ps1, robots.txt and the four
    # .sha256 files.
    #
    # robots.txt in particular: until it was added to site/, the live
    # /robots.txt was a CLOUDFLARE MANAGED DEFAULT that blocked every AI
    # crawler and was in nobody's version control. Copying the file here is
    # only half the fix — the managed-robots.txt feature must also be turned
    # off in the Cloudflare dashboard, or the edge keeps shadowing yours. The
    # file's own header comment has the check that tells you which one you are
    # actually serving.
    #
    # Set `root` in your existing server block if it is not already set; the
    # line here is the aaPanel default for this domain and is commented out
    # so it cannot conflict with the one the panel wrote.
    location / {
        # root /www/wwwroot/yangble5.com;
        index index.html;
        try_files $uri $uri/ =404;

        # WHY default_type text/plain: nginx's mime.types has no entry for
        # .sh, .ps1 or .sha256, so they fall through to `default_type`, which
        # panel configs set to application/octet-stream at http level. That
        # makes a browser DOWNLOAD install.sh instead of showing it. The
        # landing page tells visitors to read the script before running it;
        # they cannot read a download. `curl | sh` is unaffected either way.
        #
        # This is safe for this webroot because it holds only .html, .sh,
        # .ps1 and .sha256. If you add images or fonts, delete these two
        # lines — .png would otherwise be served as text/plain.
        default_type text/plain;
        charset utf-8;

        # Inherits Cache-Control: public, max-age=300 from $yb5_cc in 2j.
        # Deliberately short: install.sh and its .sha256 must never be served
        # as a stale pair from a CDN edge. If you lengthen it, purge
        # Cloudflare on every release.
    }


# =============================================================================
# PART 4 — AFTER YOU PASTE THIS IN
# =============================================================================
#
#   nginx -t                    # ALWAYS. See AAPANEL.md §5 for the reload
#                               # that does not disturb your other sites.
#
# Then, from a machine that is NOT the VPS (bash deploy/smoke_test.sh does
# all of this and more):
#
#   curl -sS  https://yangble5.com/health              # 200, {"status":"ok"}
#   curl -sS  https://yangble5.com/api/health          # 200, same body
#   curl -si  https://yangble5.com/v0/management/api-keys | head -1   # 404
#   curl -si  https://yangble5.com/admin/keys | head -1               # 404
#   curl -fsS https://yangble5.com/install.sh | head -3 # the real script
#
# THE SECURITY HEADERS, which is the check this deployment actually failed.
# Eight lines, not zero. If you get zero, PART 2j is not in the running
# config — see the note at the top of PART 2j; do not conclude "Cloudflare
# handles it", because Cloudflare does not:
#
#   curl -sSI https://yangble5.com/ | grep -icE \
#     'content-security-policy|x-content-type-options|x-frame-options|referrer-policy|strict-transport-security|cross-origin-|permissions-policy'
#
# And the one that says PART 3d landed too — `text/plain`, not
# `application/octet-stream`, so a visitor can READ the script the landing
# page tells them to read before running:
#
#   curl -sSI https://yangble5.com/install.sh | grep -i '^content-type:'
#
# And the one that matters, because it is the one naive configs fail —
# events must arrive PROGRESSIVELY, not in a single burst at the end:
#
#   curl -N -sS https://yangble5.com/v1/messages \
#     -H "Authorization: Bearer $YANGBLE5_API_KEY" \
#     -H 'content-type: application/json' \
#     -d '{"model":"yangble5","max_tokens":64,"stream":true,
#          "messages":[{"role":"user","content":"count slowly to twenty"}]}'
#
# If that dumps everything at once, work down this list in order:
#   1. proxy_buffering off        — present, and not overridden in a location?
#   2. gzip off                   — present in the /v1/ block?
#   3. add_header in a location   — did you add one, and lose PART 2j?
#   4. Cloudflare                 — retest with the record grey-clouded.
#      cloudflare.md → "Response buffering".
#
# Rollback is in AAPANEL.md §6. It is two commands and it is tested before
# you need it, not after.
# =============================================================================
